  "prompt": "My mom makes me eat less than my BMR for weight loss. what should I do?",
  "response": "It's important to approach weight loss in a healthy and sustainable way. Eating less than your Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR) can be counterproductive and potentially harmful. Here are some steps you can take:\n\n1. **Educate Yourself:** Understand your BMR and caloric needs. Your BMR is the number of calories your body needs to perform basic functions like breathing and digestion. Consuming fewer calories than this can lead to muscle loss, nutrient deficiencies, and metabolic slowdown.\n\n2. **Communicate:** Have a conversation with your mom about your concerns. Explain the risks associated with eating too little and express your desire to adopt a healthier approach to weight loss.\n\n3. **Consult a Professional:** Seek advice from a registered dietitian, nutritionist, or healthcare provider. They can help you create a personalized and balanced diet plan that ensures you're getting the nutrients you need while losing weight safely.\n\n4. **Focus on Balanced Diet:** Aim for a diet that includes a variety of foods from all food groups\u2014protein, healthy fats, carbohydrates, fruits, and vegetables. This approach helps ensure you're not just losing weight, but also maintaining overall health.\n\n5. **Exercise:** Incorporate regular physical activity into your routine. Exercise contributes to weight loss and overall well-being. Strength training can help preserve muscle mass during weight loss.\n\n6. **Monitor Your Health:** Pay attention to how your body responds to your diet and exercise. Look out for signs of nutrient deficiencies or other health issues, and seek medical advice if needed.\n\n7. **Mental Health:** Don't neglect your mental and emotional well-being. Extreme diets can lead to stress and unhealthy relationships with food.\n\nRemember, sustainable weight loss comes from healthy, balanced habits rather than extreme restrictions. Your health should always be your priority.",
